 volume develops and extends the insights of the noted scholar Thomas M. Izbicki into the so-called medieval/modern divide. The contributors include a wide array of eminent international scholars from the fields of History, Theology, Philosophy, and Political Science, all of whom explore how medieval ideas framed and shaped the thought of later centuries. This sometimes involved the evolution of intellectual principles associated with the definition and imposition of religious orthodoxy. Also addressed is the Great Schism in the Roman Church that set into question the foundations of ecclesiology. In the same era, philosophical and theoretical innovations reexamined conventional beliefs about metaphysics, epistemology and political life, perhaps best encapsulated by the fifteenth-century philosopher, theologian and political theorist Nicholas of Cusa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aCivilization, Medieval. 0aPhilosophy, Medieval. 0aPolitical sciencezEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSchism, The Great Western, 1378-1417. 0aSocial changezEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aTheologyxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 4aAbendländisches Schisma. 4aKonziliarismus. 4aModerne. 4aNikolaus, von Kues, Kardinal. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aGreat Schism.  aModernity.  aNicholas of Cusa.  aconciliarism.  aheresy.1 aBellitto, Christopher M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristianson, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuclow, Donald F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFudge, Thomas A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIzbicki, Thomas M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoch, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu